22:33.986 --> 22:38.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Another factor?
Years of
building tension among house
Republicans finally

22:38.224 --> 22:43.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
burst, forcing out House Speaker
John Boehner.
But, on his way out, Boehner
pushed through

22:43.562 --> 22:48.334 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tough bills, like raising the
debt ceiling.

22:48.367 --> 22:53.872 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In the end, Republicans
compromised with themselves,
boosting the military and other
priorities,

22:53.906 --> 22:59.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but at the cost of raising the
deficit. That
said, if you think all of this
means a productive

22:59.211 --> 23:01.880 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
2016, think again.

23:01.914 --> 23:06.485 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Congress typically doesn't pass
major legislation
in an election year.

23:06.518 --> 23:12.157 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Lisa
Desjardins.

23:12.191 --> 23:24.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: It's been called the
scientific
breakthrough of the year, and a
development

23:24.036 --> 23:30.142 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
that could revolutionize
medicine. It's all
about a way of editing genes,
known as CRISPR.

23:30.175 --> 23:35.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The new method allows scientists
to snip out
a faulty section of DNA and
replace specific

23:35.981 --> 23:42.087 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
genes in living cells.
Researchers have long
edited genes in the lab, but
CRISPR is cheaper,

23:42.121 --> 23:47.192 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
far more precise, and could even
be used in
DNA found in eggs and sperm.

23:47.226 --> 23:50.829 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It has lots of promise, but it
has raised
many concerns too.

23:50.863 --> 23:55.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We explore those questions with
Jennifer Doudna,
a professor at the University of
California,

23:55.734 --> 24:00.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Berkeley, who helped develop
this breakthrough,
and Paul Knoepfler, a biologist
and writer

24:00.339 --> 24:02.908 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
from at University of
California, Davis.

24:02.941 --> 24:04.743 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Welcome to you both.

24:04.777 --> 24:09.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jennifer Doudna, I'm going to
start by just
asking you to define in
laywoman's language

24:09.815 --> 24:11.550 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
gene editing and CRISPR.

24:11.583 --> 24:14.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER DOUDNA, University of
California,
Berkeley: Well, I would say gene
editing is

24:14.853 --> 24:21.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a method of making very precise
changes to
the DNA in a cell, and the
CRISPR methodology

24:21.593 --> 24:26.365 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
allows scientists to do that
with just really
unprecedented precision.

24:26.398 --> 24:30.102 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: So, there is a
targeted, practical
use for this?

24:30.135 --> 24:33.038 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JENNIFER DOUDNA: Indeed,
actually many.

24:33.072 --> 24:38.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a technology that operates
in basically
all types of cells and allows
very precise

24:38.177 --> 24:43.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
changes to be made to the
genetic code that
allows scientists to do things
like explore

24:43.315 --> 24:47.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the function of genes and also,
in principle,
correct mutations that cause
disease.

24:47.920 --> 24:53.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: So, give me an
example of how
this would be applied
practically. Blood diseases,

24:53.092 --> 24:55.494 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for instance? Eyes? What kind of
uses?

24:55.527 --> 25:00.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER DOUDNA: Well, I think,
in the future,
there are very exciting
applications to cure

25:00.766 --> 25:04.903 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
diseases in the blood and
potentially in the
eye and potentially in other
kinds of tissues

25:04.937 --> 25:06.672 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
as well.

25:06.705 --> 25:09.908 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think a lot of people are
excited about
the blood, because it's a tissue
where, in

25:09.942 --> 25:15.314 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
principle, at least, we can
deliver this kind
of technology to cells outside
the body, and

25:15.347 --> 25:18.283 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
then put those corrected cells
back into a
patient.

25:18.317 --> 25:21.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Paul Knoepfler, I
know this is
already in use in some labs
around the country.

25:21.887 --> 25:26.058 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do you find it exciting or do
you see it a
little bit troubling?

25:26.091 --> 25:29.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL KNOEPFLER, University of
California,
Davis: It's actually very
exciting. I have

25:29.795 --> 25:35.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
been working on gene editing in
the lab, in
test tubes and in rodents for 15
or 20 years.

25:35.534 --> 25:40.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And CRISPR really represents,
you know, a
transformative technology. I
would say it

25:40.973 --> 25:44.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- you know, if you put a number
on it, it's
probably, you know, 10 times
better than what

25:44.943 --> 25:46.645 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
we used to do.

25:46.678 --> 25:51.650 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in a sense, this allows us
to do all
kinds of new research, but it's
almost too

25:51.683 --> 25:57.089 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
good, because I think it's also
kind of opening
the door to a new frontier of
gene editing

25:57.122 --> 25:58.957 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in human beings.

25:58.991 --> 26:02.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Let's talk about
that new frontier
for a moment, Mr. Knoepfler,
because it seems

26:02.861 --> 26:07.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to me that, when I think of gene
editing,
I think of being able to go in
and actually

26:07.232 --> 26:13.272 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
change outcomes, change what a
baby looks
like, change who the baby is,
for instance,

26:13.305 --> 26:14.907 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the womb.

26:14.940 --> 26:17.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is this something that CRISPR
would allow,
not right now, but at some
point?

26:17.543 --> 26:20.312 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL KNOEPFLER: You know, it is
possible in
the future.

26:20.345 --> 26:24.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, right now, the vast
majority of us
who are working on CRISPR, you
know, we really

26:24.483 --> 26:30.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have no interest in making
designer babies.
We want to advance science
through research.

26:30.289 --> 26:35.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, you know, I think our top
priority, if
we do go into humans, it's going
to be preventing

26:35.761 --> 26:38.297 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
specific genetic diseases.

26:38.330 --> 26:41.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think where we run into
trouble is,
there is sort of a spectrum of
what could

26:41.467 --> 26:47.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
be done with this, and there is
certainly
some proponents of actually
enhancing people

26:47.206 --> 26:52.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and going the designer baby
route. And that's
something that I find very
concerning.

26:52.311 --> 26:56.515 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So I have been speaking out on
that. And I
actually just came out with a
new book called

26:56.548 --> 27:00.352 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
"GMO Sapiens" where I address
some of the
concerns here.

27:00.385 --> 27:05.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Jennifer Doudna,
you're nodding
in agreement, but you're also
aware that the

27:05.457 --> 27:11.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
National Institutes of Health
have put a moratorium
on funding this kind of
research. Does that

27:11.096 --> 27:13.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
mean that there are widespread
concerns about
its uses?

27:13.732 --> 27:18.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER DOUDNA: Well, I think
there is widespread
awareness that this is powerful
technology

27:18.971 --> 27:22.574 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that needs to be employed in a
prudent fashion.

27:22.608 --> 27:26.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As you may know, I have been
quite involved
in the ethical discussions
around this technology.

27:26.945 --> 27:31.884 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And, in fact, earlier in
December of this
year, we had a meeting in
Washington, D.C.,

27:31.917 --> 27:37.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that was sponsored by three
different national
academies in China, the U.K. and
the U.S.

27:37.689 --> 27:39.525 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to discuss this very issue.

27:39.558 --> 27:44.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so this is an area where
many scientists
and clinicians and obviously
other stakeholders

27:44.696 --> 27:46.565 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are getting involved in the
discussion.

27:46.598 --> 27:52.271 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And also another
stakeholder in
this are private companies. Even
if the government

27:52.304 --> 27:56.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
won't fund the research, what's
to stop a
private company from forging
ahead on this?

27:56.775 --> 27:59.511 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JENNIFER DOUDNA: Exactly. I
mean, right now,
nothing.

27:59.545 --> 28:04.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, this is something where, I
think, again,
the scientific community needs
to step forward

28:04.216 --> 28:08.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and really point out what the
issues are with
the technology that can be
employed for the

28:08.854 --> 28:11.623 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
kind of genome editing that
could affect human
evolution.

28:11.657 --> 28:16.194 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Paul Knoepfler,
could we be sacrificing
accuracy for speed?

28:16.228 --> 28:18.063 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL KNOEPFLER: I think so.

28:18.096 --> 28:22.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, you know, CRISPR is
much more accurate
than the kinds of technology we
used in the

28:22.601 --> 28:28.941 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
past, but I think it's not
accurate enough
right now to actually use it
either in humans

28:28.974 --> 28:34.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or for the creation of a new
human being,
say, with a corrected genetic
mutation.

28:34.046 --> 28:38.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, so, one of the exciting
things about
CRISPR is that it's evolving so
fast that

28:38.984 --> 28:44.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think even by, say, the middle
of 2016,
it's going to be more accurate,
it's going

28:44.523 --> 28:48.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to be more powerful than it is
today. So,
you know, perhaps one of the
challenges is

28:48.961 --> 28:53.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
going to be, where do we stop
and say, you
know, it's good enough, it's
accurate enough,

28:53.665 --> 28:56.702 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
where we could, say, use it for
gene therapy
or something like that?

28:56.735 --> 29:00.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: When we're talking
about clinical
trials to use it for something
like that,

29:00.572 --> 29:05.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are we anticipating that could
happen relatively
soon, Jennifer Doudna?

29:05.410 --> 29:06.244 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

29:06.278 --> 29:08.013 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL KNOEPFLER: Oh, sorry. Go
ahead.

29:08.046 --> 29:10.415 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER DOUDNA: Well, my guess
would be,
within a couple of years, we
will see initial

29:10.449 --> 29:14.786 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
clinical trials. That's what I'm
guessing,
based on the pace of the field
right now.

29:14.820 --> 29:17.456 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And, Paul Knoepfler,
you agree
with that, obviously?

29:17.489 --> 29:19.391 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL KNOEPFLER: Yes, I think so.

29:19.424 --> 29:25.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, for gene therapy work,
it would be
appropriate to go ahead with it
in the next

29:25.330 --> 29:32.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
few years. Where I'm more
concerned is, there
is fertility clinics, some
philosophers and

29:32.170 --> 29:37.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
others who are saying, let's not
stop there,
let's go ahead and let's try to
make better

29:37.242 --> 29:39.144 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
human beings.

29:39.177 --> 29:45.017 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think we can kind of put
better in quotation
marks, but who decides what's
better? And,

29:45.050 --> 29:51.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you know, if they were trying to
make a child
who has dodged a bone disease,
you know, what

29:51.590 --> 29:56.662 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if that child is not just
healthy, their bones
are better than anyone else's in
the world,

29:56.695 --> 29:58.630 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
you know?

29:58.664 --> 30:04.503 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, you know, would you
resist the temptation
perhaps to get stronger bones,
bigger muscles?

30:04.536 --> 30:09.841 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I guess I feel like it's a tough
thing to
draw the line between medical
application

30:09.875 --> 30:11.677 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and human enhancement.

30:11.710 --> 30:15.847 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Well, then, how do
you draw that
line? Say you want to be able to
find a cure

30:15.881 --> 30:20.285 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for sickle cell anemia and this
gets you a
lot closer to it faster.

30:20.318 --> 30:25.157 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jennifer Doudna, what happens
if, say, that
makes for a better person who
has to say to

30:25.190 --> 30:29.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
their mate 10 years down the
road, 20 years
down the road, by the way, I am
genetically

30:29.194 --> 30:30.829 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
altered, before we have
children?

30:30.862 --> 30:34.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JENNIFER DOUDNA: Well, yes, I
think that's
still a bit in the future.

30:35.000 --> 30:40.672 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I do think that the CRISPR
technology offers
a way to discover the function
of genes. And

30:40.706 --> 30:46.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
one of the things that currently
limits the
field is just the lack of
knowledge about

30:46.645 --> 30:50.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the genetic basis for all sorts
of traits,
including disease, but other
things as well.

30:50.315 --> 30:54.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think this is where we
will see a
lot of active work in the
immediate future,

30:54.186 --> 30:55.954 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is really on the research front.

30:55.987 --> 30:58.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Well, let me assume
for a moment
that we figure out where these
lines should

30:58.724 --> 31:02.227 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
be drawn and this is an
unalloyed good in
the long run.

31:02.260 --> 31:08.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I want to ask each of you,
finally, Paul Knoepfler,
starting with you, how big a
leap forward

31:08.400 --> 31:09.401 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
is this?

31:09.434 --> 31:12.337 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PAUL KNOEPFLER: I think it's
transformative.

31:12.370 --> 31:18.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it's as big as nuclear
physics or
something like that. I think,
you know, one

31:18.210 --> 31:23.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the most exciting and also
frightening
aspects of it is that it's going
to enable

31:23.582 --> 31:29.387 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
us to literally change
ourselves, you know,
and kind of hack into the human
code.

31:29.421 --> 31:34.826 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think, you know, that's
unprecedented
in history. And so, as we're
doing that, as

31:34.860 --> 31:40.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we're changing ourselves, I
think, you know,
whether that's in five years, 10
years, I

31:40.165 --> 31:46.071 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
do think someone's going to do
that. And so,
you know, that's very exciting
again, but

31:46.104 --> 31:52.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
terrifically scary, because, you
know, what
will we become? What will we
become in the

31:52.410 --> 31:54.112 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
future?

31:54.146 --> 31:55.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Well, Jennifer
Doudna, how do
we balance that out? This
hacking into the

31:55.814 --> 32:00.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
human code sounds exciting to a
scientist,
but might sound scary to a
layperson.

32:00.352 --> 32:02.154 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JENNIFER DOUDNA: Right.

32:02.187 --> 32:07.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, again, my feeling all
along is has been
that I feel, as Paul just said,
very, very

32:07.192 --> 32:12.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
excited about the potential for
this technology
to affect human societies in the
future in

32:12.264 --> 32:16.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
positive ways. But I do think
that it's a
powerful technology. There's no
question.

32:16.968 --> 32:19.371 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it needs to be handled with
appropriate
caution.

32:19.404 --> 32:23.441 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Jennifer Doudna,
Paul Knoepfler,
thank you both very much.

32:23.475 --> 32:26.545 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PAUL KNOEPFLER: Thank you.

32:26.578 --> 32:31.383 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JENNIFER DOUDNA: Thank you.

32:31.416 --> 32:41.560 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Since January 2013,
journalist
Paul Salopek has tracked ancient
man's path

32:41.593 --> 32:45.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
out of Africa, what he calls the
Out of Eden
Walk.

32:45.197 --> 32:50.569 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, we take another look at
Hari Sreenivasan's
visit and walk with Paul, as
they trace the

32:50.602 --> 32:54.039 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
footsteps of early man on his
global trek.

32:54.072 --> 32:58.476 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The
fog-shrouded fields
and rolling hills of Southern
Georgia are

32:58.510 --> 33:04.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
much more than a waypoint for
Paul Salopek.
We were nearing the ancient city
and archaeological

33:04.282 --> 33:06.051 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
site of Dmanisi.

33:06.084 --> 33:08.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK, Fellow, National
Geographic:
So, Dmanisi is finally in sight
and this is

33:08.386 --> 33:13.925 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
probably one of the most
important human migration
sites outside of Africa proper.

33:13.959 --> 33:18.530 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Salopek is
following the
path humans took after the Ice
Age, 70,000

33:18.563 --> 33:23.969 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to 100,000 years ago. But here
in Dmanisi,
that path is much older.

33:24.002 --> 33:28.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Along these green and jagged
river gorges,
we have walked in one form or
another for

33:29.007 --> 33:34.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
nearly two million years. The
history here
is stacked high, part of what
Salopek calls

33:34.746 --> 33:40.285 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the layer cake effect of the
Caucasus. With
a happy dog welcoming us, we
passed what was

33:40.318 --> 33:45.190 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
likely an outer defensive tower
of the 1,400-year-old
city of Dmanisi.

33:45.223 --> 33:47.325 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This has been a crossroads for a
long time.

33:47.359 --> 33:50.829 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: From day one. And
pretty much
everybody invaded it.

33:50.862 --> 33:52.631 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And was this a
trading route?

33:52.664 --> 33:56.601 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: This was a silk
road trading
route city, a big shining city
on the hill,

33:56.635 --> 34:02.374 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
very rich, until the Mongols
came and plundered
it. And then they were here a
few hundred

34:02.407 --> 34:05.176 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
years until the Georgians and
Armenians pushed
them out.

34:05.210 --> 34:10.382 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: It's an
archaeological gold
mine. With the summer digging
season finished,

34:10.415 --> 34:14.419 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we arrived at a sort of bunk
house for archaeologists
to rest for the night.

34:14.452 --> 34:18.156 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SALOPEK: If we did, by some
miracle,
get a clear sky, it really will
change everything

34:18.189 --> 34:19.991 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
completely.

34:20.025 --> 34:26.798 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The next
morning, a miracle
had indeed swept away the fog.
Within what

34:26.831 --> 34:31.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you're seeing is nearly two
million years
of history, the medieval city,
whose walls

34:31.836 --> 34:37.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
still stand, built on top of a
Bronze Age
settlement that's 5,000 years
old, and still

34:37.776 --> 34:44.316 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
beneath that, the 1.8
million-year-old remains
of one of modern human's
earliest ancestors.

34:44.349 --> 34:49.888 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Salopek, Dima Bit-Suleiman, his
walking partner
in Georgia, and I were joined by
the director

34:49.921 --> 34:55.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Georgia's National Museum,
David Lordkipanidze,
for the walk up to the hilltop
dig site.

34:55.994 --> 34:58.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID LORDKIPANIDZE, Director,
Georgia National
Museum: What we found here, it
changed our

34:58.530 --> 35:07.706 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
understanding about early traces
of human
evolution, about first dispersal
of our ancestors.

35:07.739 --> 35:15.880 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, also, it's completely
changed our views
about who, when left Africa and
how they were

35:15.914 --> 35:18.249 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
looking and what they were doing
also.

35:18.283 --> 35:20.118 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What were
these guys doing?

35:20.151 --> 35:23.421 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID LORDKIPANIDZE: These guys
were enjoying
life here.

35:23.455 --> 35:25.223 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

35:25.256 --> 35:29.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Enjoying life
in a place
much more lush and temperate 1.8
million years

35:29.294 --> 35:34.599 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ago. Thanks to bones discovered
here at the
same latitude as Boston, we know
this was

35:34.632 --> 35:40.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
