they were
prey. But, you see, it's lucky
for archaeology,

35:56.221 --> 35:56.554 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
right?

35:56.588 --> 35:57.722 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

35:57.756 --> 36:00.025 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Bad day for
them, good day
for you.

36:00.058 --> 36:03.028 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID LORDKIPANIDZE: Yes. We are
very lucky.

36:03.061 --> 36:07.365 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And that lucky
day came
10 years ago, with the discovery
of a skull,

36:07.399 --> 36:14.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the last of five found that is
the remarkably
complete skull of an ancient
ancestor of modern

36:14.272 --> 36:16.875 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
man.

36:16.908 --> 36:19.110 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
So this is it?

36:19.144 --> 36:23.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
David took us to the National
Museum in the
capital city of Tbilisi to see
the actual

36:23.848 --> 36:30.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
skulls kept in a vault and
handled with kid
gloves, because they are indeed
national treasures.

36:30.555 --> 36:31.656 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
This is how old?

36:31.689 --> 36:34.059 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID LORDKIPANIDZE: This is 1.8
million years
old.

36:34.092 --> 36:39.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The brain
capacity was about
40 percent of ours, and they
stood about 5

36:39.431 --> 36:44.803 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
feet tall. The skull has
features of three
different species, a possible
snapshot in

36:44.836 --> 36:51.743 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
time of evolution. An older
adult, probably
a male, was among those found.
And the toothless,

36:51.776 --> 36:55.280 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
worn jawbone might tell us more
than just
size and age.

36:55.313 --> 37:00.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID LORDKIPANIDZE: It means it
was weak
individual who could survive
only with help

37:00.885 --> 37:08.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of others. And I think that
Dmanisi shows
also the first traces of
compassions and solidarity

37:08.526 --> 37:10.361 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in Homo erectus.

37:10.395 --> 37:14.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, Homo
erectus, even though
they had a brain that was a
third our size,

37:14.999 --> 37:17.202 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they still cared for somebody
other than themselves.

37:17.235 --> 37:22.140 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID LORDKIPANIDZE: One of the
human characters
could be taking on others.

37:22.173 --> 37:24.008 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Taking care of
others.

37:24.042 --> 37:26.344 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How did these guys get to
Dmanisi? Why did
they leave?

37:26.377 --> 37:31.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID LORDKIPANIDZE: See, I
