42:34.218 --> 42:35.953 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL POLLAN: Yes.

42:35.987 --> 42:40.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The word is up for grabs,
because food has
changed more in the last 75
years than it

42:40.425 --> 42:45.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has in the previous 10,000. We
have learned
how to process foods in whole
new ways. And

42:45.696 --> 42:50.735 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I would argue that we're
creating things that
don't deserve to be called by
that beautiful

42:50.768 --> 42:53.704 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
word. And so I call them edible
food-like
substances.

42:53.738 --> 42:58.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You talk about
how we're all
caught up in the grips of
something you call

42:58.643 --> 43:01.446 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
nutritionism. Now, define that
and explain
the problem.

43:01.479 --> 43:03.314 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL POLLAN: Sure.

43:03.347 --> 43:07.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yes, nutritionism, it's not a
science, although
it's supposedly based on
nutrition science.

43:07.785 --> 43:12.557 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's an ideology. It's a way of
thinking about
food that I think is at the root
of our national

43:12.590 --> 43:16.961 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
eating disorder. It's why we're
so anxious
and confused about food.

43:16.994 --> 43:21.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nutritionism basically argues
that foods,
the important things about foods
are the nutrients

43:21.866 --> 43:25.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they contain. It's not the whole
food itself.
We don't look at a piece of
meat. We should

43:25.837 --> 43:31.142 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
be thinking about saturated fat
and heme iron
and things like that.

43:31.175 --> 43:36.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It also, by extension, argues,
if the nutrient
is what is important in food,
and nutrients

43:36.681 --> 43:41.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are invisible to most people, we
need experts
to tell us how to eat. And I
think that's

43:41.085 --> 43:42.720 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a very dangerous idea.

43:42.753 --> 43:46.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And therefore
being led by
the advertising in some cases,
right?

43:46.290 --> 43:48.025 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MICHAEL POLLAN: Well, exactly.

43:48.059 --> 43:52.864 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The expert message we hear the
most is the
message of industry, which
spends more than

43:52.897 --> 43:59.103 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
$30 billion a year to market
food to us. By
comparison, the government's
voice, the doctor's

43:59.136 --> 44:05.877 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
voice, the voice of sanity gets
drowned out.
And so we walk into a
treacherous landscape

44:05.910 --> 44:10.848 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the supermarket, where we're
bombarded
with health claims that are very
often deceptive.

44:10.882 --> 44:16.420 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, these are
added nutrients.
This is fat, low fat, nonfat.
And give me

44:16.454 --> 44:17.855 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
-- give us a good example.

44:17.889 --> 44:20.725 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL POLLAN: Well, I mean,
the cereal aisle
is a wonderful example.

44:20.758 --> 44:24.595 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You walk down there and you find
cereals that
are going to prevent heart
attacks and extend

44:24.629 --> 44:30.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
your life span, I mean, just
outrageous claims
that are made. And the
government has been

44:30.067 --> 44:34.138 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
trying to tone them down, but
every time they
have a new rule, industry comes
up with another

44:34.171 --> 44:36.707 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
way to make the same claims.

44:36.741 --> 44:41.078 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yet, keep in mind that, when
you're looking
at the really healthy food and
you're over

44:41.112 --> 44:47.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in produce, notice how quiet it
is. The broccoli
is not screaming about its whole
grain goodness

44:47.852 --> 44:49.720 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
or the fact that it has no fat.

44:49.754 --> 44:54.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, that's an important rule of
thumb, that
the healthiest foods in the
supermarket are

44:54.158 --> 44:55.426 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the quietest.

44:55.459 --> 44:56.994 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The quieter the
food, the better
for you, huh?

44:57.028 --> 44:59.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL POLLAN: The silence of
the yams, we
should listen to.

44:59.997 --> 45:01.732 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

45:01.766 --> 45:05.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You know, the
film looks at
different ways of changing
behavior. And if

45:05.403 --> 45:09.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there's a core message that came
through to
me, is that there really are a
lot of things

45:09.707 --> 45:14.712 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that one can do individually and
community-wise.
You look at a lot of examples.

45:14.745 --> 45:18.683 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL POLLAN: Well, this is a
very solvable
problem.

45:18.716 --> 45:23.821 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's true that the food
landscape has gotten
treacherous. On the other hand,
we still know

45:23.854 --> 45:28.693 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what to do. And a lot of the
science in the
film ends up being really a
confirmation of

45:28.726 --> 45:34.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
common sense, that if you eat
lots of plants,
you're better off than eating
lots of meat.

45:34.065 --> 45:38.469 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not to say meat is evil or
it's bad for
you. It's not. It's very
nutritious food,

45:38.502 --> 45:42.273 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but we eat way too much of it,
both for our
health and for the health of the
environment.

45:42.306 --> 45:46.477 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a lot of interesting
things about
how the environment shapes our
eating. So,

45:46.510 --> 45:51.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for example, the size of the
plates you use
at home, merely by reducing the
diameter of

45:51.816 --> 45:56.420 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the plates by an inch or two,
you can reduce
your food consumption by 20
percent or 30

45:56.454 --> 45:58.556 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
percent without even thinking
about it.

45:58.589 --> 46:04.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we're being -- getting all
these messages
about that's -- that 16 ounces
is the proper

46:04.161 --> 46:11.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
size for a soda, or that, you
know, a burrito
should be two pounds. And we
tend to do what

46:11.168 --> 46:15.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we're told. We have a thing
called a unit
bias. If that's how much you
pour in the glass,

46:15.906 --> 46:17.675 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that's a proper portion.

46:17.708 --> 46:22.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's crazy. So, we need to
kind of take
back control of our diet from
industry, which

46:22.713 --> 46:27.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is really trying to get us at
every stage
to eat more and drink more than
we really

46:27.585 --> 46:29.353 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
even want to.

46:29.387 --> 46:32.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And what about at
the policy
level? Because we are at another
moment, right,

46:32.423 --> 46:37.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
where the government -- new
dietary guidelines
are in the works, coming out
pretty soon.

46:37.428 --> 46:39.196 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL POLLAN: Yes.

46:39.230 --> 46:43.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Every five years, the government
endeavors
to tell us what to eat. We don't
really listen,

46:43.467 --> 46:47.204 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
but it's an interesting
conversation. And
they will be coming out in a few
weeks, a

46:47.238 --> 46:52.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
new set of dietary guidelines.
And, you know,
hopefully, they will be more
progressive than

46:52.043 --> 46:53.811 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the past.

46:53.844 --> 46:57.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, in the past, they have
really fallen
into that nutritionism frame of
saying, you

46:57.214 --> 47:01.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
know, eat more of this nutrient,
eat less
of that nutrient, this is evil,
this is good.

47:01.619 --> 47:05.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Need to remember that those
guidelines have
been wrong in the past. They
were telling

47:05.723 --> 47:10.928 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
us for many years to eat less
fat, that fat
was what was going to make us
fat and give

47:10.961 --> 47:15.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
us heart disease. Well, in fact,
that consensus
-- this is something we cover in
detail in

47:15.266 --> 47:20.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the film -- the consensus around
the low-fat
campaign has completely
collapsed, even though

47:20.905 --> 47:23.874 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
your cardiologist probably
hasn't told you.

47:23.908 --> 47:29.113 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The links between fat and heart
disease or
the links between fat and
obesity are actually

47:29.146 --> 47:30.915 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
very slender.

47:30.948 --> 47:34.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And I have to ask
you, Michael,
finally, to the extent that this
is sort of

47:34.085 --> 47:40.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a personal quest for you in the
film and in
your books, where do you break
the rules?

47:40.291 --> 47:44.695 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What's your worst eating habit?
What's the
Michael Pollan bad eating?

47:44.729 --> 47:51.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL POLLAN: Well, like
everybody, I struggle
with quantity, when to stop. I
love to eat.

47:51.302 --> 47:55.973 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I love food. I have my junk food
favorites.
I have kind of a weakness for
Cracker Jacks.

47:56.006 --> 47:57.808 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I will admit that.

47:57.842 --> 48:03.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But my point in the film is, we
shouldn't
stress so much about that, and
the issue is

48:03.447 --> 48:09.754 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not the special occasion food.
It's the everyday
default practice. It's not
having a soda.

48:09.787 --> 48:11.789 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's having a soda every day.

48:11.822 --> 48:16.961 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, if you get the basic
default down,
you can indulge. I mean, one of
my food rules

48:16.994 --> 48:22.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is from -- borrowed from Oscar
Wilde, all
things in moderation, including
moderation.

48:22.933 --> 48:25.803 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, "In
Defense of Food."

48:25.836 --> 48:27.138 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Michael Pollan, thanks so much.

48:27.171 --> 48:31.609 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MICHAEL POLLAN: Thank you,
Jeffrey.

48:31.642 --> 48:42.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Kind of staying with
that theme,
finally tonight, the holidays
seemed a good

48:42.253 --> 48:48.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
time for an encore look at
author Ylonda Gault's
take on another particularly
challenging family

48:48.425 --> 48:51.295 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
issue: the personality of the
bragging parent.

48:51.328 --> 48:55.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
YLONDA GAULT, Author: It will
start innocently,
a chance run-in.

48:56.000 --> 49:02.406 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I will see a fellow mom at the
grocery store
or the park, maybe a coffee
shop. I will say,

49:02.439 --> 49:05.776 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
hey, girl. We will hug. At least
I will, because
I'm a hugger.

49:05.810 --> 49:11.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I will compliment her outfit.
She may notice
my new highlights. We will trade
innocent

49:11.115 --> 49:18.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
gossip. I will ask about her
work, then the
family, to which she will
respond with a sigh,

49:18.722 --> 49:24.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as though fatigued, because, for
moms, every
season touts tired as the new
black.

49:24.461 --> 49:32.870 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Thus begins the humble brag,
feigning exasperation.
Said mom will half-giggle and
wax self-mocking.

49:32.903 --> 49:40.511 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, Sophie scored 2,200 on her
®MDNM/SATs,
despite this slacker mom, who
forgot to get

49:40.544 --> 49:45.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
new calculator batteries. And
Zach's fourth
grade teacher recommended him
for advanced

49:45.950 --> 49:47.751 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
calculus.

49:47.785 --> 49:53.524 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Meanwhile, his dad and I don't
still get new
math, old math, or even everyday
math. These

49:53.557 --> 49:56.727 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
kids, I tell you.

49:56.760 --> 50:02.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A wan smile will wash over my
face. It's the
expression I usually reserve for
my 8-year-old

50:02.733 --> 50:08.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when he's regaling with my
intricate details
of obscure superheroes and their
powers.

50:08.772 --> 50:15.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When she laughs and throws her
head back,
I do the same thing on the
outside. Inside,

50:15.045 --> 50:21.518 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I wince, and whisper to myself,
bless her
heart, as momma would say.

50:21.552 --> 50:27.157 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For black people, those sweet
little words
are a nice way of saying, how
pitiful.

50:27.191 --> 50:33.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a gracious phrase, and I
mean it in the
best possible way, because a
part of me truly

50:33.063 --> 50:39.703 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
aches to see a grown woman,
smart and accomplished
in her own right, boasting about
her children

50:39.737 --> 50:42.706 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as though they were prized
heifers at the
county fair.

50:42.740 --> 50:49.179 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's odd to me, because,
growing up, momma
always played down what my
siblings and I

50:49.213 --> 50:56.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
did. It may be a black thing,
but I think
it's also an old-school thing.
No one wanted

50:56.921 --> 51:00.691 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
their kids to get too
big-headed, I suppose.

51:00.724 --> 51:06.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Importantly, parenting wasn't an
extreme sport
back in the day. And, remember,
there was

51:06.263 --> 51:12.569 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
no Facebook. Social media posts
are the lifeblood
of the humble braggart.

51:12.603 --> 51:18.242 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I get it. They feel less secure
in their own
worth, so tethered are the
kiddos to their

51:18.275 --> 51:23.013 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
own self-image, the offsprings'
accomplishments
become their own.

51:23.047 --> 51:29.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Intellectually, I know most
studies will show
that mothers and fathers
hell-bent on this

51:29.753 --> 51:35.826 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
image of perfection desperately
need the world
to take note of their kids'
awesomeness. It's

51:35.859 --> 51:44.601 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a way of saying, see, my kids
are great. Therefore,
I am great. Look at me. See? I'm
a great parent.

51:44.635 --> 51:46.403 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Really, I am.

51:46.437 --> 51:54.011 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Do they believe it? Sadly, I
don't think so.
It's not that these parents
don't have good

51:54.044 --> 52:00.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
kids. I mean, all kids are good,
right, just
like all babies are -- ahem --
cute.

52:00.884 --> 52:08.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
See, all moms lie. As the humble
braggart
prattles on, I pretend to
listen. And when

52:08.258 --> 52:18.635 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
she's done, I put on my best
girlfriend face
and try to sound super
astonished. I say,

52:18.669 --> 52:24.408 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
wow. Go, you.

